<section xml:id="section-modules">
    
    <title>Python Packages and NumPy</title>

    <introduction>
        Python packages and Python libraries are a collection of functions and modules centered around a common theme. 
        (For example, NumPy is the standard open source scientific computing package.)
        In this section we will learn how to import a Python package or library and use functions from that package.    
    </introduction>

    <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Import a Python package or library (our example NumPy).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use functions from a Python package.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>

      <p>
        NumPy is an open source scientific computing package that allows you to use standard
        mathematical functions and constants like sine or pi. 
        NumPy also allows you to work with arrays of numbers so you can efficiently perform computations. 
      </p>

      <sage language='python'>
        <input>
          #first import the package numpy
          import numpy

          #compute sin(2) 
          x = numpy.sin(2)
          print(x)
        </input>
      </sage>


      <p>
        Note to call a function from an imported package you must use the syntax <c>package.function</c>.
        To avoid retyping the name of the package every time, you can rename the package as you import.  
      </p>

      <exercise>
        <p>
          Replace the import line in the above code with <c>import numpy as np</c>. 
          Then rename the function <c>np.sin()</c> and re-run.
        </p>
      </exercise>


      <sage language='python'>
        <input>
          #first import the package numpy
          import numpy

          #decide the radius of the circle
          radius = 4
          
          #compute the area using the actual value of pi
          circle_area = numpy.pi*radius**2

          print(circle_area)
        </input>
      </sage>

      <remark>
        Note that you first need to import the package. 
        Note also to call a variable or function from an imported package 
        you use package.variable or package.function to tell Python where to find that variable or function. 
      </remark>

      <p>
        Renaming a package 
      </p>


      <sage language='python'>
        <input>
          import numpy 
          X = numpy.array([1,2,3,4])
          print(2*X)
        </input>
      </sage>


      <p>
        Do something with arrays here 
      </p>


      <sage language='python'>
        <input>
          import numpy 
          X = numpy.array([1,2,3,4])
          print(2*X)
        </input>
      </sage>

